# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phaser-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:phaser-framework/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 was first released in a public-facing form on 22 January 2008, with a major update and "W3C Recommendation" status in October 2014.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 is intended to subsume not only HTML 4 but also XHTML1 and even the DOM Level 2 HTML itself.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 includes detailed processing models to encourage more interoperable implementations; it extends, improves, and rationalizes the markup available for documents and introduces markup and application programming interfaces (APIs) for complex web applications.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] For the same reasons, HTML5 is also a candidate for cross-platform mobile applications because it includes features designed with low-powered devices in mind.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Many new syntactic features are included.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] To enrich the semantic content of documents, new page structure elements such as `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`, `<aside>`, `<nav>`, and `<figure>` are added.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] New attributes were introduced, some elements and attributes were removed, and others such as `<a>`, `<cite>`, and `<menu>` were changed, redefined, or standardized.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The APIs and Document Object Model (DOM) are now fundamental parts of the HTML5 specification, and HTML5 also better defines the processing for any invalid documents.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group (WHATWG) began work on the new standard in 2004.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] At that time, HTML 4.01 had not been updated since 2000, and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) was focusing future developments on XHTML 2.0.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In 2009, the W3C allowed the XHTML 2.0 Working Group's charter to expire and decided not to renew it.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The Mozilla Foundation and Opera Software presented a position paper at a World Wide Web Consortium workshop in June 2004, focusing on developing technologies that are backward-compatible with existing browsers, including an initial draft specification of Web Forms 2.0.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The workshop concluded with a vote—8 for, 14 against—for continuing work on HTML.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Immediately after the workshop, WHATWG was formed to start work based upon that position paper, and a second draft, Web Applications 1.0, was also announced.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The two specifications were later merged to form HTML5.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The HTML5 specification was adopted as the starting point of the work of the new HTML working group of the W3C in 2007.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] WHATWG's Ian Hickson (Google) and David Hyatt (Apple) produced W3C's first public working draft of the specification on 22 January 2008.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Many web browsers released after 2009 support HTML5, including Google Chrome 3.0, Safari 3.1, Firefox 3.5, Opera 10.5, Internet Explorer 9 and later.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] While some features of HTML5 are often compared to Adobe Flash, the two technologies are very different.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Both include features for playing audio and video within web pages, and for using vector graphics.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] However, HTML5 on its own cannot be used for animation or interactivity – it must be supplemented with CSS3 or JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] There are many Flash capabilities that have no direct counterpart in HTML5 (see Comparison of HTML5 and Flash).
[src:phaser-framework/html5] This sparked a debate in web development circles suggesting that, while HTML5 provides enhanced functionality, developers must consider the varying browser support of the different parts of the standard as well as other functionality differences between HTML5 and Flash.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In early November 2011, Adobe announced that it would discontinue the development of Flash for mobile devices and reorient its efforts in developing tools using HTML5.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 25 July 2017, Adobe announced that both the distribution and support of Flash would cease by the end of 2020.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Adobe itself officially discontinued Flash on 31 December 2020 and all Flash content was blocked from running in Flash Player as of 12 January 2021.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 14 February 2011, the W3C extended the charter of its HTML Working Group with clear milestones for HTML5.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In May 2011, the working group advanced HTML5 to "Last Call", an invitation to communities inside and outside W3C to confirm the technical soundness of the specification.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C developed a comprehensive test suite to achieve broad interoperability for the full specification by 2014, which was the target date for recommendation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In January 2011, the WHATWG renamed its "HTML5" specification *HTML Living Standard*.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C nevertheless continued its project to release HTML5.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In July 2012, WHATWG and W3C decided on a degree of separation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] W3C will continue the HTML5 specification work, focusing on a single definitive standard, which is considered a "snapshot" by WHATWG.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The WHATWG organization continues its work with HTML5 as a "living standard".
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The concept of a living standard is that it is never complete and is always being updated and improved.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] New features can be added but functionality will not be removed.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In December 2012, W3C designated HTML5 as a Candidate Recommendation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The criterion for advancement to W3C Recommendation is "two 100% complete and fully interoperable implementations".
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 16 September 2014, W3C moved HTML5 to Proposed Recommendation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 28 October 2014, HTML5 was released as a W3C Recommendation, bringing the specification process to completion.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 1 November 2016, HTML 5.1 was released as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 14 December 2017, HTML 5.2 was released as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Additionally, the retirement included HTML 4.0, HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0, and XHTML 1.1.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML 5.1, HTML 5.2 and HTML 5.3 were all retired on 28 January 2021, in favour of the HTML living standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C ceded authority over the HTML and DOM standards to WHATWG on 28 May 2019, as it considered that having two standards is harmful.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The HTML Living Standard is now authoritative.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] However, W3C will still participate in the development process of HTML.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Before the ceding of authority, W3C and WHATWG had been characterized as both working together on the development of HTML5, and yet also at cross purposes ever since the July 2012 split.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C "HTML5" standard was snapshot-based (HTML5, HTML 5.1, etc.) and static, while the WHATWG "HTML living standard" is continually updated.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The relationship had been described as "fragile", even a "rift", and characterized by "squabbling".
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In at least one case, namely the permissible content of the `<cite>` element, the two specifications directly contradicted each other (as of July 2018), with the W3C definition allowing a broader range of uses than the WHATWG definition.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The "Introduction" section in the WHATWG spec (edited by Ian "Hixie" Hickson) is critical of W3C, e.g.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The two entities signed an agreement to work together on a single version of HTML on 28 May 2019.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C proposed a greater reliance on modularity as a key part of the plan to make faster progress, meaning identifying specific features, either proposed or already existing in the spec, and advancing them as separate specifications.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some features that were removed from the original HTML5 specification have been standardized separately as modules, such as Microdata and Canvas.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Technical specifications introduced as HTML5 extensions such as Polyglot markup have also been standardized as modules.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some W3C specifications that were originally separate specifications have been adapted as HTML5 extensions or features, such as SVG.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some features that might have slowed down the standardization of HTML5 were or will be standardized as upcoming specifications, instead.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 introduces elements and attributes that reflect typical usage on modern websites.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some of them are semantic replacements for common uses of generic block (`<div>`) and inline (`<span>`) elements, for example `<nav>` (website navigation block), `<footer>` (usually referring to bottom of web page or to last lines of HTML code), or `<audio>` and `<video>` instead of `<object>`.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some deprecated elements from HTML 4.01 have been dropped, including purely presentational elements such as `<font>` and `<center>`, whose effects have long been superseded by the more capable Cascading Style Sheets.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] There is also a renewed emphasis on the importance of client-side JavaScript used to create dynamic web pages.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The HTML5 syntax is no longer based on SGML despite the similarity of its markup.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] It has, however, been designed to be backward-compatible with common parsing of older versions of HTML.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] It comes with a new introductory line that looks like an SGML document type declaration, `<!DOCTYPE html>`, which triggers the standards-compliant rendering mode.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Since 5 January 2009, HTML5 also includes *Web Forms 2.0*, a previously separate WHATWG specification.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In addition to specifying markup, HTML5 specifies scripting application programming interfaces (APIs) that can be used with JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Existing Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces are extended and *de facto* features documented.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Not all of the above technologies are included in the W3C HTML5 specification, though they are in the WHATWG HTML specification.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some related technologies, which are not part of either the W3C HTML5 or the WHATWG HTML specification, are as follows.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 cannot provide animation within web pages.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Additional JavaScript or CSS3 is necessary for animating HTML elements.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Animation is also possible using JavaScript and HTML 4, and within SVG elements through SMIL, although browser support of the latter remains uneven as of 2011.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] XML documents must be served with an XML Internet media type (often called "MIME type") such as `application/xhtml+xml` or `application/xml`, and must conform to strict, well-formed syntax of XML.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] XHTML5 is simply XML-serialized HTML5 data (that is, HTML5 constrained to XHTML's strict requirements, e.g., not having any unclosed tags), sent with one of XML media types.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML that has been written to conform to both the HTML and XHTML specifications and therefore produces the same DOM tree whether parsed as HTML or XML is known as polyglot markup.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] HTML5 is designed so that old browsers can safely ignore new HTML5 constructs.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] In contrast to HTML 4.01, the HTML5 specification gives detailed rules for lexing and parsing, with the intent that compliant browsers will produce the same results when parsing incorrect syntax.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Although HTML5 now defines a consistent behavior for "tag soup" documents, those documents do not conform to the HTML5 standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] According to a report released on 30 September 2011, 34 of the world's top 100 Web sites were using HTML5 – the adoption led by search engines and social networks.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Another report released in August 2013 has shown that 153 of the *Fortune 500* U.S. companies implemented HTML5 on their corporate websites.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Since 2014, HTML5 is at least partially supported by most popular layout engines.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The following is a cursory list of differences and some specific examples.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] W3C Working Group publishes "HTML5 differences from HTML 4", which provides a complete outline of additions, removals and changes between HTML5 and HTML4.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 18 January 2011, the W3C introduced a logo to represent the use of or interest in HTML5.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Unlike other badges previously issued by the W3C, it does not imply validity or conformance to a certain standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] As of 1 April 2011, this logo is official.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] When initially presenting it to the public, the W3C announced the HTML5 logo as a "general-purpose visual identity for a broad set of open web technologies, including HTML5, CSS, SVG, WOFF, and others".
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Some web standard advocates, including The Web Standards Project, criticized that definition of "HTML5" as an umbrella term, pointing out the blurring of terminology and the potential for miscommunication.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Three days later, the W3C responded to community feedback and changed the logo's definition, dropping the enumeration of related technologies.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The W3C then said the logo "represents HTML5, the cornerstone for modern Web applications".
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Industry players including the BBC, Google, Microsoft, and Apple Inc. have been lobbying for the inclusion of Encrypted Media Extensions (EME), a form of digital rights management (DRM), into the HTML5 standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] As of the end of 2012 and the beginning of 2013, 27 organizations including the Free Software Foundation have started a campaign against including digital rights management in the HTML5 standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] However, in late September 2013, the W3C HTML Working Group decided that Encrypted Media Extensions, a form of DRM, was "in scope" and will potentially be included in the HTML 5.1 standard.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] WHATWG's "HTML Living Standard" continued to be developed without DRM-enabled proposals.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Manu Sporny, a member of the W3C, said that EME would not solve the problem it was supposed to address.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] Opponents point out that EME itself is just an architecture for a DRM plug-in mechanism.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] The initial enablers for DRM in HTML5 were Google and Microsoft.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] On 14 May 2014, Mozilla announced plans to support EME in Firefox, the last major browser to avoid DRM.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] While promising to "work on alternative solutions", Mozilla's Executive Chair Mitchell Baker stated that a refusal to implement EME would have accomplished little more than convincing many users to switch browsers.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] This decision was condemned by Cory Doctorow and the Free Software Foundation.
[src:phaser-framework/html5] As of December 2023, the W3C defended their formation of the EME standard, stating: "Encrypted Media Extensions (EME) brings greater interoperability, better privacy, security, accessibility and user experience in viewing movies and TV on the Web".
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
