[src:phaser-framework/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:phaser-framework/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser uses both a canvas and WebGL renderer internally and can automatically swap between them based on browser support.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] This allows for fast rendering across desktop and mobile.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] It uses the Pixi.js library for rendering.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Games can be deployed to iOS, Android and native desktop apps via third-party tools like Apache Cordova.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Richard Davey announced the first release of Phaser on a blog post in April 2013.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Version 1.0 was released in September 2013, incorporating the Pixi.js library for rendering.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] The last official version of Phaser 2 was 2.6.2, but to allow improvements to the stable version while working on Phaser 3, a new repository was created: Phaser CE (Community Edition).
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] The last official version of Phaser 3 was 3.90.0.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Most elements and features of the framework were rebuilt from scratch using a fully modular structure and data-orientated approach.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser 3 included a brand-new custom WebGL renderer designed for modern 2D games.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Since then, much of the documentation and examples for users has been completed, and the majority of features have been implemented.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Development of Phaser 4 was announced August 19, 2019.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] It mainly focuses on a rewrite of the renderer designed for performant and modern 2D games, while keeping the API mostly the same.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] The first version of Phaser 4 was released on April 10th, 2026.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser can run in any web browser that supports the canvas element.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Games made with phaser are developed either in JavaScript or TypeScript.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] A web server is required to load resources like images, sounds, and other game files, as browsers require web pages to access files only from the same origin.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser can be either rendered in WebGL or a canvas element, with an option to use WebGL if the browser supports it, or if a device does not support it, it will fall back to Canvas.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser ships with three physics systems: Arcade Physics, Ninja Physics and P2.JS.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Arcade Physics is for high-speed AABB collision only.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Ninja Physics allows for complex tiles and slopes, which are adequate for level scenery, and P2.JS is a full-body physics system, which supports constraints, springs, and polygon among others.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] As of phaser 3.6, there are two major physics engines.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] There is also a less known engine similar to Arcade called Impact.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Arcade is probably the most used out of the three, since it is fast and easy to use.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] It uses axis-aligned (not rotated) rectangles and circles for collision detection on top of all basic physics engine features, like gravity, acceleration and drag.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Its downside is that its features are limited.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Complex hitboxes can be very difficult to make out of the supported shapes and multiple objects in close proximity can cause stability issues.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Matter is the more advanced physics engine but its complexity also rises with the added features.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Matter is capable of simulating very realistic full-body physics.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] It supports a multitude of features such as rigid, compound and composite bodies, elastic collisions, stable stacking and physical properties like mass and density.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Impact holds many similarities to Arcade but brings some useful advantages.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] For example, Impact can have slopes in its tilemaps, which is not possible with Arcade's axis-aligned rectangles.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] However, the downside to this is that developers have to use the Impact engine's developer's own "Weltmeister" editor for creating tilemaps.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser supports spritesheets and texture atlases, which include multiple frames or character animations.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Developers can use frame sequences to craft animations.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser's animation sequence capability allows developers to effortlessly create animation sequences for sprites, including control over looping, speed, and frame rates.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] From simple character movements to complex special effect animations.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Furthermore, Phaser offers a built-in tweening engine for crafting smooth transition animations.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] This is particularly useful for effects like fading, scaling, rotating, and can also be used for other complex special effect animations.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Phaser allows developers to manage and play web audio and HTML5 audio, providing a rich set of audio effect control options, including volume, mute, looping, fading in and out, and sound positioning.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] These attributes can be adjusted as needed.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Additionally, Phaser supports preloading of audio files, ensuring sound plays without delay, ready for immediate playback, delivering a better gaming experience.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Cocos2d-x: Cocos2d-x is a cross-platform 2D/3D game development framework.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Compared with Phaser, it supports more native platforms, such as iOS and Android.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] However, Phaser is based on HTML5, which makes it easier to integrate with modern web technologies and is suitable for rapid iteration and deployment of web platforms.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Unity: Unity is a well-known game development engine in the industry, supporting both 2D and 3D game development.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Compared with Phaser, Unity provides more powerful editor tools and wider platform support.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] But Phaser is relatively lightweight, and the entry barrier may be lower for beginners, especially those who only want to focus on web game development.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Three.js: Three.js is a cross-browser Javascript and application programming interface used to create and display animated 3D computer graphics in a web browser using WebGL.
[src:phaser-framework/phaser-game-framework] Instead, Phaser focuses more on browser-side game development.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:phaser-framework/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL programs consist of control code written in JavaScript, and shader code written in OpenGL ES Shading Language (GLSL ES, sometimes referred to as ESSL), a language similar to C or C++.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL code is executed on a computer's GPU.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL is designed and maintained by the non-profit Khronos Group.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] On February 9, 2022, Khronos Group announced WebGL 2.0 support from all major browsers.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] From 2024, a new graphics API, WebGPU, is being developed to supersede WebGL.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGPU provides extended capabilities, a more modern interface, and direct GPU access, which is useful for demanding graphics as well as AI applications.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL 1.0 is based on OpenGL ES 2.0 and provides an API for 3D graphics.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] It uses the HTML5 canvas element and is accessed using Document Object Model (DOM) interfaces.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] It guarantees the availability of many optional extensions of WebGL 1.0, and exposes new APIs.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Automatic memory management is provided implicitly by JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Like OpenGL ES 2.0, WebGL lacks the fixed-function APIs introduced in OpenGL 1.0 and deprecated in OpenGL 3.0.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] This functionality, if required, has to be implemented by the developer using shader code and JavaScript.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Shaders in WebGL are written in GLSL and passed to the WebGL API as text strings.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] The WebGL implementation compiles these strings to GPU code.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] This code is executed for each vertex sent through the API and for each pixel rasterized to the screen.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL evolved out of the Canvas 3D experiments started by Vladimir Vukićević at Mozilla.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Vukićević first demonstrated a Canvas 3D prototype in 2006.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] By the end of 2007, both Mozilla and Opera had made their own separate implementations.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] In early 2009, the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group started the WebGL Working Group, with initial participation from Apple, Google, Mozilla, Opera, and others.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Version 1.0 of the WebGL specification was released March 2011.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] An early application of WebGL was Zygote Body.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] In November 2012 Autodesk announced that they ported most of their applications to the cloud running on local WebGL clients.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] These applications included Autodesk Fusion and AutoCAD.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Development of the WebGL 2 specification started in 2013 and finished in January 2017.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] The specification is based on OpenGL ES 3.0.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] First implementations are in Firefox 51, Chrome 56 and Opera 43.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Almost Native Graphics Layer Engine (ANGLE) is an open source graphic engine which implements WebGL 1.0 (2.0 which closely conforms to ES 3.0) and OpenGL ES 2.0 and 3.0 standards.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] It is a default backend for both Google Chrome and Mozilla Firefox on Windows platforms and works by translating WebGL and OpenGL calls to available platform-specific APIs.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] WebGL is widely supported by modern browsers.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] However, its availability depends on other factors, too, like whether the GPU supports it.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] The official WebGL website offers a simple test page.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] More detailed information (like what renderer the browser uses, and what extensions are available) can be found at third-party websites.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Some such libraries were ported to JavaScript from other languages.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Examples of libraries that provide high-level features include A-Frame (VR), BabylonJS, PlayCanvas, three.js, OSG.JS, Google’s model-viewer and CopperLicht.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Web3D also made a project called X3DOM to make X3D and VRML content run on WebGL.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] There has been an emergence of 2D and 3D game engines for WebGL, such as Unreal Engine 4 and Unity.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] The Stage3D/Flash-based Away3D high-level library also has a port to WebGL via TypeScript.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] A more light-weight utility library that provides just the vector and matrix math utilities for shaders is sylvester.js.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] It is sometimes used in conjunction with a WebGL specific extension called glUtils.js.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] There are also some 2D libraries built atop WebGL, like Cocos2d-x or Pixi.js, which were implemented this way for performance reasons in a move that parallels what happened with the Starling Framework over Stage3D in the Flash world.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] The WebGL-based 2D libraries fall back to HTML5 canvas when WebGL is not available.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Removing the rendering bottleneck by giving almost direct access to the GPU has exposed performance limitations in the JavaScript implementations.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Some were addressed by asm.js and WebAssembly (similarly, the introduction of Stage3D exposed performance problems within ActionScript, which were addressed by projects like CrossBridge).
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] As with any other graphics API, creating content for WebGL scenes requires using a 3D content creation tool and exporting the scene to a format that is readable by the viewer or helper library.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Desktop 3D authoring software such as Blender, Autodesk Maya or SimLab Composer can be used for this purpose.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] In particular, Blend4Web allows a WebGL scene to be authored entirely in Blender and exported to a browser with a single click, even as a standalone web page.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] There are also some WebGL-specific software such as CopperCube and the online WebGL-based editor Clara.io.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Online platforms such as Sketchfab and Clara.io allow users to directly upload their 3D models and display them using a hosted WebGL viewer.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] Starting from Firefox Version 27, Mozilla has given Firefox built-in WebGL tools that allow the editing of vertices and fragment shaders.
[src:phaser-framework/webgl] A number of other debugging and profiling tools have also emerged.
